04244nam a22007335i 9780231500661DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012051155  a(OCoLC)979904032  a97802315006617 a10.7312/negr160462doi  a(DE-B1597)459161  a(OCoLC)857800071  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB3998b.N4413 2013 4aB3998b.N4413 2015 7aPHI0270002bisacsh04a199.4922231 aNegri, Antonio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpinoza for Our Time :bPolitics and Postmodernity /cAntonio Negri. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tTranslator’S Note -- tIntroduction: Spinoza And Us -- t1. Spinoza: A Heresy Of Immanence And Of Democracy -- t2. Potency And Ontology: Heidegger Or Spinoza -- t3. Multitude And Singularity In The Development Of Spinoza’S Political Thought -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAntonio Negri, one of the world's leading scholars on Baruch Spinoza (1632–1677) and his contemporary legacy, offers a straightforward explanation of the philosopher's elaborate arguments and a persuasive case for his ongoing relevance. Responding to a resurgent interest in Spinoza's thought and its potential application to contemporary global issues, Negri demonstrates the thinker's special value to politics, philosophy, and related disciplines.Negri's work is both a return to and an advancement of his initial affirmation of Spinozian thought in The Savage Anomaly. He further defends his understanding of the philosopher as a proto-postmodernist, or a thinker who is just now, with the advent of the postmodern, becoming contemporary. Negri also connects Spinoza's theories to recent trends in political philosophy, particularly the reengagement with Carl Schmitt's "political theology," and the history of philosophy, including the argument that Spinoza belongs to a "radical enlightenment." By positioning Spinoza as a contemporary revolutionary intellectual, Negri addresses and effectively defeats twentieth-century critiques of the thinker waged by Jacques Derrida, Alain Badiou, and Giorgio Agamben.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSpinoza, Benedictus de - Criticism and interpretation. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aGangle, Jonathan "Rocco".1 aGangle, Rocco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCuaig, William.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/negr1604640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231500661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231500661/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK